              <div type="commentary">
                  <p xml:lang="en">Three other examples of the signaculum are respectively in Granada [coming from the excavation of the forum of the ancient Roman city of Basti, today Baza (Granada, Spain); see M. Pastor Muñoz, Epigraphica Granatensis, III, in FlorIlib, 22, 267-295];
                      in Rome [from Viterbo?, now in the Gregorian Etruscan Museum of the Vatican Museums, Falcioni collection, inv. 15958; see L. M. Caliò, La collezione Bonifacio Falcioni, Città del Vaticano, 2000, 311, no. 539] 
                      and in Florence [unknown provenance, now in the National Archaeological Museum, Strozzi collection, inv. 10; see A. Buonopane-Ch. Gabrielli, Signacula ex aere. La collezione del Museo Archeologico Nazionale di Firenze, Roma 2021, 78, no 46].</p>
                  <p>The four signacula fall within the typology of multiple signacula "ad exemplum", according to the classification proposed in 
                      I. Di Stefano Manzella, V. Valchera, G. Cicala, S. Braito, A. Vella, Signacula ex aere: dossier Agáthȏn (quattro multipli e quattro impronte su tegole e mattoni), in BMMP, XXX, 2012, 35-62,
                      i.e. the signacula derive by approximation from a common reference model / archetype.</p>
              </div>
